<div class='question-begin'>Question 4</div><div class='question-body'>


Make a plot to show how dominance changes for each ape as they get older.  

::: {.callout-tip collapse="true"}
#### Hints

In [Chapter 5: Longitudinal MLM - #exploring-the-data](https://uoepsy.github.io/lmm/05_long.html#exploring-the-data){target="_blank"} we made a facet for each cluster (each participant). That was fine because we had only 20 people. In this dataset we have 168! That's too many to facet. We could try using `group` aesthetic instead, to plot multiple lines on the same plot, or we could just plot a sample of our apes. This is all just an initial look at the data, after all. 

:::



</div><p class="question-end"></p>




<div style="display:none;">



Here's a line for each ape, and a facet for each species:  



::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(apedat, aes(x = age, y = dominance, col = species))+
  geom_line(aes(group = ape)) + 
  facet_wrap(~species) + 
  guides(col="none")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](02ex_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-17-1.png){fig-align='center' width=80%}
:::
:::




It's kind of hard to see the trend for each ape, so let's also make a separate little linear model for each ape:  




::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(apedat, aes(x = age, y = dominance, col = species))+
  geom_smooth(aes(group = ape), method=lm, se=FALSE) + 
  facet_wrap(~species) + 
  guides(col="none")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](02ex_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-18-1.png){fig-align='center' width=80%}
:::
:::




Alternatively, let's take a sample of apes, and plot the same stuff but facetted:



::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
apedat |>
  # choose the rows where ape ID is one of a random sample of 16 ape IDs
  filter(ape %in% sample(unique(apedat$ape), 16) ) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = dominance, col = species))+
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method=lm, se=FALSE)+
  facet_wrap(~ape)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](02ex_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-19-1.png){fig-align='center' width=80%}
:::
:::







</div><p class="solution-end"></p>






<div class='question-begin'>Question 5</div><div class='question-body'>


Recenter the `age` variable on 1, which is the youngest ages that we've got data on for any of our species.   

Then fit a model that estimates the differences between primate species in how dominance changes over time.  


::: {.callout-tip collapse="true"}
#### Hints

think slowly about "differences between primate species in how dominance changes over time".  

- "how dominance changes over time" -- sounds like `dominance ~ time`
- so differences between primate species in this would require the interaction `dominance ~ time * species`


:::




</div><p class="question-end"></p>




<div style="display:none;">






::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
apedat$age = apedat$age-1 

m.full <- lmer(dominance ~ 1 + age * species + (1 + age | ape), data = apedat)
```
:::






</div><p class="solution-end"></p>





<div class='question-begin'>Question 6</div><div class='question-body'>


__*Do*__ primate species differ in the growth of dominance?  
Perform an appropriate test/comparison.  

::: {.callout-tip collapse="true"}
#### Hints

This is asking about the `age*species` interaction, which in our model is represented by 3 parameters. To assess the overall question, it might make more sense to do a model comparison.  

:::




</div><p class="question-end"></p>




<div style="display:none;">






::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
m.int <- lmer(dominance ~ 1 + age + species + (1 + age | ape), data = apedat)

anova(m.int, m.full)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
Data: apedat
Models:
m.int: dominance ~ 1 + age + species + (1 + age | ape)
m.full: dominance ~ 1 + age * species + (1 + age | ape)
       npar    AIC    BIC  logLik deviance  Chisq Df Pr(>Chisq)   
m.int     9 806.67 849.11 -394.34   788.67                        
m.full   12 801.16 857.74 -388.58   777.16 11.517  3   0.009237 **
---
Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
```


:::
:::

::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

:::




:::int

Species differ in how dominance changes over adolescence ($\chi^2(3) = 11.52, p = 0.009$).  

:::




</div><p class="solution-end"></p>





<div class='question-begin'>Question 7</div><div class='question-body'>


Plot the average model predicted values for each age.  

Before you plot.. do you expect to see straight lines? (remember, not every ape is measured at age 2, or age 3, etc).  


::: {.callout-tip collapse="true"}
#### Hints

This is like taking `predict()` from the model, and then then grouping by `age`, and calculating the mean of those predictions. However, we can do this more easily using `augment()` and then some fancy `stat_summary()` in ggplot (see [the lecture](https://uoepsy.github.io/msmr/2425/lectures/msmr_lec02-2_LinearLDA.html#17){target="_blank"}).  


:::




</div><p class="question-end"></p>




<div style="display:none;">



Averaging fitted values would give us straight lines _if_ every ape had data at all ages, but in our study we have some apes with only 2 data points, and each ape has different set of ages (e.g., one ape might be measured at age 3, 6, and 10, another ape might be at ages 2 and 16).  




::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
library(broom.mixed)

augment(m.full) |>
ggplot(aes(age,dominance, color=species)) +
  # the point ranges are our observations
  stat_summary(fun.data=mean_se, geom="pointrange") + 
  # the lines are our average predictions  
  stat_summary(aes(y=.fitted, linetype=species), fun=mean, geom="line")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](02ex_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-23-1.png){fig-align='center' width=80%}
:::
:::






</div><p class="solution-end"></p>





